SIMPLE: remain
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Remain
<hw>Re*main"</hw> <pr>(r?-m?n")</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Remained</conjf>
<pr>(-m?nd")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Remaining</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF. <ets>remaindre</ets>,
<ets>remanoir</ets>, L. <ets>remanere</ets>; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- +
<ets>manere</ets> to stay, remain. See <er>Mansion</er>, and cf.
<er>Remainder</er>, <er>Remnant</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To stay behind while others withdraw; to be left
after others have been removed or destroyed; to be left after a number
or quantity has been subtracted or cut off; to be left as not included
or comprised.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Gather up the fragments that <qex>remain</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>John
vi. 12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of whom the greater part <qex>remain</qex> unto this present, but
some are fallen asleep.</q> <rj><qau>1 Cor. xv. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That . . . <qex>remains</qex> to be proved.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To continue unchanged in place, form, or condition,
or undiminished in quantity; to abide; to stay; to endure; to
last.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Remain</qex> a widow at thy father's house.</q> <rj><qau>Gen.
xxxviii. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Childless thou art; childless <qex>remain</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To continue; stay; wait; tarry; rest; sojourn;
dwell; abide; last; endure.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Remain</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Remain
<hw>Re*main"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To await; to be left to.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The easier conquest now <qex>remains</qex> thee.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Remain</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Remain
<hw>Re*main"</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>State of remaining;
stay.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Which often, since my here <qex>remain</qex> in England,⟦br⟧
I 've seen him do.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is left; relic; remainder; -- chiefly in
the plural.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>remains</xex> of old Rome.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When this <qex>remain</qex> of horror has entirely subsided.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Specif., in the plural:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd>
<def>That which is left of a human being after the life is gone; relics;
a dead body.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Old warriors whose adored <qex>remains</qex>⟦br⟧
In weeping vaults her hallowed earth contains!</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>The posthumous works or productions, esp. literary
works, of one who is dead; as, Cecil's</def> <xex>Remains</xex>.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Remainder</ent>⟦br⟧
